<title>GREECE: GREEK FINMIN EMPLOYEES TELL MIN BRACKET CREEP HURTS THEM.</title>
<headline>GREEK FINMIN EMPLOYEES TELL MIN BRACKET CREEP HURTS THEM.</headline>
<dateline>ATHENS 1996-12-10</dateline>
<text>
<p>Representatives of Greek finance ministry employees told National Economy Minister Yannos Papandoniou that the bracket creep and the abolition of tax breaks would reduce their disposable income, said state Athens News Agency (ANA).</p>
<p>The representatives said that they would have to pay 180,000 drachmas more in taxes annually because of the new tax regime, it said.</p>
<p>Papandoniou was quoted as saying that the issue of tax exemptions was not negotiable for the government and the relevant draft bill would soon be voted in parliament.</p>
<p>Tax and customs officials have announced a 48-hour strike for December 17 and 18. --Dimitris Kontogiannis, Athens Newsroom +301 3311812-4</p>
